ic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Atherton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place near Manchester named Atherton, from the Old English personal name <i>Æthelhere</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’.","English: habitational name from Hatherton, Staffordshire, from Old English <i>haguthorn</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘the hill where hawthorn grows’.","English (East Anglia): topographic name from Middle English <i>at ther doune</i> ‘(dweller) on the hill’ (Old English <i>æt thǣre dūne</i>). Through confusion of <i>-don</i> and <i>-ton</i>, <i>Attherdoune</i> was altered to <i>Atherton</i>, <i>Adderton</i>, and <i>Atterton</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Atherton was born in 1280, in Atherton, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir Hugh de Atherton, was 30 and his mother, Agnes DE MOLYNEUX, was 25. He married Emma De Atherton, born de AinTree about 1295, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1330, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1280–1330":"1280–1330","1274–1319":"1274–1319","1325–1396":"1325–1396","1250–1292":"1250–1292","1255–1339":"1255–1339","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1274":"1274","1250":"1250","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","circa 1295":"umbes 1295","1255":"1255","circa 1292":"1292","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Malling, Kent, England":"Atherton, Lancashire, England","Atherton, Lancashire, England":"Atherton, Lancashire, England","Glodwich, Lancashire, England":"Atherton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1280–1330":"1280–1330","1274–1319":"1274–1319","1325–1396":"1325–1396","1250–1292":"1250–